&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/geby/"&gt;geby (off for a while)&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/geby/4404287237/" title="John R on a cliff at sea"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2709/4404287237_b6ecfdecb8_m.jpg" width="240" height="158" alt="John R on a cliff at sea" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This ship grounded NW of Tromsoe 26.12.2000. I had to abort my vacation and served as a resuce officer. Empty the oil. The ship broke up some days later... On it's way from Liverpool to Murmansk, capitan from Inda, never been north before..&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/geby/"&gt;geby (off for a while)&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/geby/4417248808/" title="Oljevern 02"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2773/4417248808_b09b463eca_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="Oljevern 02" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A specialized ship for oil spill rescue, berthed in Vadsø. Have been assisting in Kirkenes port, a russian trawler &amp;quot;Tobago&amp;quot; caught fire, and Oljevern 02 was standby vessel if some oil started to leak from &amp;quot;Tobago&amp;quot;. You find shots of the fire on &lt;a href="http://www.finnmarken.no" rel="nofollow"&gt;www.finnmarken.no&lt;/a&gt;  I'm a member of the oil spill group Depot 12 in Vadsø after I served in the Coastguard. See my oil spill set also&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/beentherephotography/"&gt;Been There Photography&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/beentherephotography/4430433964/" title="Crash 01"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4036/4430433964_fbe5c2de85_m.jpg" width="240" height="161" alt="Crash 01" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We had some excitement in north Midland this morning.  A crude oil tanker took a corner too fast and rolled over, spilling roughly 2100 gallons of crude on to the city streets.  The Stripes Convenience Store and a nearby strip mall were evacuated to avoid any hydrogen sulfide poisoning.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Here the dragon wagons are trying to right the tanker so it can be transported from the scene.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
No word at this time of any injuries to the driver.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Thanks again to Midland PD for allowing me up on the embankment to grab the shot.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/48675443@N03/"&gt;Adam bd&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/48675443@N03/4531868803/" title="Poor Caddy"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2696/4531868803_d7ea0703ce_m.jpg" width="240" height="180" alt="Poor Caddy" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Venice, Louisiana after Katrina.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/48675443@N03/"&gt;Adam bd&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/48675443@N03/4540910648/" title="Venice, Louisiana"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4054/4540910648_d9115fec2d_m.jpg" width="240" height="130" alt="Venice, Louisiana" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Venice is the same (cursed apparently) town nearest the oil rig that exploded and sank into the Gulf of Mexico on April 22, 2010.  If you look at its location on a map, you'll see it is surrounded precariously almost on all sides by the Mississippi Delta and River.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Here it is a few months after hurricane Katrina hit in 2005.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/gypsyfaephotography/"&gt;GypsyFae&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/gypsyfaephotography/4568137609/" title="Happy Beltane..."&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4049/4568137609_94040f177a_m.jpg" width="240" height="194" alt="Happy Beltane..." /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;18 April 2009.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Greenwood // Seattle, Washington&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Happy Beltane my friends.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I really feel for the sea turtles, whales, birds, and other wildlife that will suffer the consequences of this major oil spill.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
This will be an environmental disaster of epic proportions. All because it is “too expensive” to move towards alternative energy.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
No, in the long run, oil is more costly. After environmental destruction, global climate change, and the cost of wars fought over resources, alternative energy is the only way to go.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Where are the “Drill baby drill” folks now? Huh? I haven’t heard a peep from Sarah Palin about this disaster. Oh, that is right. “It is a small price we pay” is what her response was on the Exxon/Valdez oil spill. And what about Obama? During is campaign he mentioned that he wanted to turn towards green energy. Now he wants to offshore drill. Politicians are a bunch of whoreshit liars. But we already knew that.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Sometimes I feel like I am one of the few environmentalists left in America. Meanwhile, people go on, driving their SUV’s and other gas guzzling vehicles, feeling sad about this, but putting it in the back of their mind.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
At least I am one person walking everywhere and taking the bus occasionally. Not a car owner. By far, owning a car is one of the worse things you can do for the environment. When I used to own a car, I felt burdened. There is no such thing as an environmentally friendly car. At least not yet. Hybrids still use gas. As do the Prius. BUT, we need cars in the world we live in now, because our lifestyle is built around cars. And this country still has a long way to go when it comes to public transportation. Europe is way ahead, with their train systems. And onto plastics. I don’t buy a lot of plastics. I often time will change my mind about buying a product if I think there is too much plastic involved. I frequent a coffee shop down the street that uses corn plastic, which is biodegradable and not made out of oil. Everything is a catch 22, it seems. I guess it doesn’t seem like a lot…but it is a step.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Unfortunately, we need government to step in to help green up the country, otherwise, in some way or another, we are all dependent on oil.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
We can find less destructive ways to support our lifestyles.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
There are those that say…(mostly the Sarah Palins and Dick Cheneys of the world)…”That way we can have Extremely HIGH gas prices and we can send millions of dollars overseas and help other nations better there economy.”&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
We’ve already been doing that for years. We currently owe China millions and millions of dollars. They are making windmills and solar panels, while we are around the globe fighting wars for oil.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
If we don’t want to become a third rate nation we need to invest in the future, not hold onto the technology of the past.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I’ve been listening all along. Informed all along.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It deeply saddens me that it takes an epic disaster like this for people to listen up.&lt;/p&gt;

