&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/cdevers/"&gt;Chris Devers&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/cdevers/4683695155/" title="BP Oil Catastrophe projected over New York City, as of 7 June 2010"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4072/4683695155_d397f31d24_m.jpg" width="240" height="159" alt="BP Oil Catastrophe projected over New York City, as of 7 June 2010" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Via &lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/" rel="nofollow"&gt;If It Was My Home&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href="http://andy.beowulfe.com/" rel="nofollow"&gt;Andy Litner&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The Google Map on &lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/" rel="nofollow"&gt;this site&lt;/a&gt; lets you visualize the extent of the BP oil spill catastrophe off the coast of New Orleans relative to any location on the Earth.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/#loc=New York, NY, USA&amp;amp;lat=40.7142691&amp;amp;lng=-74.0059729&amp;amp;x=-74.0059729&amp;amp;y=40.7142691&amp;amp;z=7" rel="nofollow"&gt;Centered on New York City&lt;/a&gt;, it would extend as far south as Philadelphia, which is over halfway to Washington, DC; it would reach as far west as Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania; it goes most of the way to Albany to the north; and to the northeast it goes right up the Rhode Island border and on to Worcester MA. And that's not to mention all of Long Island, most of New Jersey, and a big chunk of the nearby Atlantic Ocean.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Center the spill near &lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/#loc=Victorville, CA, USA&amp;amp;lat=34.5361067&amp;amp;lng=-117.2911565&amp;amp;x=-117.2911565&amp;amp;y=34.5361067&amp;amp;z=7" rel="nofollow"&gt;Victorville, California&lt;/a&gt;, and it reaches all the way from Los Angeles to Las Vegas. Use &lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/#loc=Westminster, London, UK&amp;amp;lat=51.5001524&amp;amp;lng=-0.1262362&amp;amp;x=-0.1262362&amp;amp;y=51.5001524&amp;amp;z=7" rel="nofollow"&gt;London&lt;/a&gt; and it covers pretty much all of southeast England; it would also cover &lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/#loc=Thun, Switzerland&amp;amp;lat=46.75258&amp;amp;lng=7.623338&amp;amp;x=7.623338&amp;amp;y=46.75258&amp;amp;z=7" rel="nofollow"&gt;all of Switzerland&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/#loc=Jerusalem District, Israel&amp;amp;lat=31.7857&amp;amp;lng=35.2007&amp;amp;x=35.2007&amp;amp;y=31.7857&amp;amp;z=7" rel="nofollow"&gt;most of Israel &amp;amp; a lot of Jordan&lt;/a&gt;, etc.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
(Just don't trust the &lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/#loc=South Pole, Antarctica&amp;amp;lat=-90&amp;amp;lng=0&amp;amp;x=0&amp;amp;y=-89.99999743867906&amp;amp;z=0" rel="nofollow"&gt;South Pole&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/#loc=North Pole,&amp;amp;lat=90&amp;amp;lng=0&amp;amp;x=0&amp;amp;y=89.99999743867906&amp;amp;z=0" rel="nofollow"&gt;North Pole&lt;/a&gt; -- apparently &amp;quot;divide by zero&amp;quot; errors make the spill act a bit funny there.)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Anyway, try it for yourself at &amp;quot;&lt;a href="http://www.ifitwasmyhome.com/" rel="nofollow"&gt;If It Was My Home&lt;/a&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

