&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/wishardofoz/"&gt;Wishard of Oz&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/wishardofoz/4691917187/" title="Day 162- SP on PCB looking for BP's oil!"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4014/4691917187_e701bdb031_m.jpg" width="240" height="172" alt="Day 162- SP on PCB looking for BP's oil!" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;June 11, 162/365 (893/1096)- Drove out to the far western end of our beach tonight to see if there was any sign of oil washing up, but all I saw was some piles of  &amp;quot;June grass&amp;quot; washed up like we get every year at this time.  I also know the oil can't be far from our clean sugary white sands along our famous little stretch of the Emerald Coast.  But the water is still beautiful and the June grass will go away in a day or two.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The oil has gotten ashore within 50 or so miles from us.  It's day 51 of the leak and BP still seems to have no clue as to how to stop it, much less how to clean all this gorgeous shoreline for years to come.  I guess BP still can't foul up the sunsets though!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Used a tripod, self timer, and one SB900 point at me to get this sunset backlight selfie!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Update:  A few hours later a 5,000 lb. tank full of hydraulic oil that was thrown from the well when it exploded washed up a few hundred feet from here . . . yikes!&lt;/p&gt;

