&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jeffhemmer/4786504384/" title="53"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4097/4786504384_fcf6066230_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="53" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Austrich, Piggy and Rat ended up doing the typical trapped-animal thing, separating their trapped feet from the rest of their bodies, which was of course very tragic. Fox and Cat kept falling over in the wind. I tried to give prospective customers some reassurance by telling them it was 'art that moves' (&amp;quot;Kunst, die bewegt und sich bewegt&amp;quot;).&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Photo by Julia Hermesmeyer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/jeffhemmer/"&gt;Jeff Hemmer&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jeffhemmer/4786504616/" title="54"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4134/4786504616_a9373b3b41_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="54" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Photo by Julia Hermesmeyer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/jeffhemmer/"&gt;Jeff Hemmer&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jeffhemmer/4786505308/" title="56"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4099/4786505308_654331ede4_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="56" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;quot;Möchten Sie Graffiti kaufen?&amp;quot;&lt;br /&gt;
Would you like to buy some graffiti? No? *hm*&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Photo by Julia Hermesmeyer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/jeffhemmer/"&gt;Jeff Hemmer&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jeffhemmer/4786505538/" title="57"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4099/4786505538_e2fa0fe34d_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="57" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This young lady was among our first guests at the stall. Unfortunately, she didn't quite see the genius behind our idea and failed to understand why it is necessary to turn street art into a product that can be sold, bought and owned.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Photo by Julia Hermesmeyer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/jeffhemmer/"&gt;Jeff Hemmer&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jeffhemmer/4786506274/" title="59"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4139/4786506274_c95f86ecb9_m.jpg" width="160" height="240" alt="59" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This lady was very interested in our products but complained she could not really experience the exquisit feel of the material through the gloves.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Her friend in turn became very interested in working for us. When asked about the working conditions at our base in Greece, Gockelmann-Stilzchen assured her that workers there had been given reassurance that, should they ever take a day off for sickness, they'd be fired.&lt;br /&gt;
(&amp;quot;Sind Ihre Arbeitskräfte ordentlich versichert?&amp;quot; - &amp;quot;Na selbstverständlich. Alle Mitarbeiter erhalten von uns die Versicherung, dass sie im Krankheitsfall umgehend ihren Arbeitsplatz verlieren.&amp;quot;)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Photo by Marco Roßnagel.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/jeffhemmer/"&gt;Jeff Hemmer&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jeffhemmer/4786506718/" title="61"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4134/4786506718_5b0e2d545b_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="61" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Overall, the performance went well, much better than I had expected. Of course, quite a large number of people walked past, even when invited to buy some graffiti. I often felt mistaken for a fool ;) A sizeable proportion of my 'customers' were fellow students who had come out to support me. But I reckon the number of strangers showing an interest in the stall was about the same.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I had several requests from tourists to pose for a photo. I doubt I'll ever get to see any of those, but it would be funny as hell :) The Disneyland effect ;)) I did some goofy waving, too, of course :)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
An elderly woman handed me 2 euro because she was convinced I was in desperate need for money. Convincing her I wasn't allowed to take money and that she should at least take one of the shopping bags in return took a lot of effort.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Two Polish exchange students from Uni Bremen seemed to take the idea seriously at first (or at least seemed to be giving me the benefit of doubt :)), until one of them remembered her Latin classes and figured out that none of the text I was giving them made any sense.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Two people, a lady and a man identifiying himself as an illustrator, didn't ask a great deal of questions and instead just congratulated me on my work.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Mostly, people that dared to approach me (I only stopped wearing the cock mask during drinking/smoking breaks and the last twenty minutes of my performance) soon figured out this was all nonsense, but we had some nice exchanges, one with an apparent father-to-be gifted with a great sense of humour was especially funny. I was glad to find nobody seemed to agree with Lorem Ipsum!'s policies. On the contrary, I also met a few individuals who seemed genuinely shocked at the ideas Gockelmann put forward. What I enjoyed most were those moments when I could detect a sense of bewilderment in people's faces.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I was also glad nobody tried to beat me up or chase me out of town :)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Photo by Marco Roßnagel.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/jeffhemmer/"&gt;Jeff Hemmer&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jeffhemmer/4786507082/" title="63"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4140/4786507082_1ab0b6f8f0_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="63" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Last but not least, thanks to Mareike, for offering us this class, and for being my best customer ;)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Photo by Marco Roßnagel.&lt;/p&gt;

