&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/carbonquilt/"&gt;CarbonQuilt&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/carbonquilt/4973486287/" title="4.9 million barrels of oil as a 1mm thick puddle over London"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4150/4973486287_e4faeab4bf_m.jpg" width="240" height="215" alt="4.9 million barrels of oil as a 1mm thick puddle over London" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;4.9 million barrels ± 10% is the National Incident Command’s Flow Rate Technical Group estimate for oil spilled by Deepwater Horizon. This graphic is an attempt to get a *feel* for that quantity of oil. It was commissioned by the BBC One Planet programme.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Note: the picture is not the size of the Deepwater Horizon slick, which covered a much larger area but was thinner than 1 mm on average. For a sense of scale of the slick see: 'If it were my home': &lt;a href="http://www.ifitweremyhome.com/disasters/bp" rel="nofollow"&gt;www.ifitweremyhome.com/disasters/bp&lt;/a&gt; &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
At 1mm thick, 4.9 million barrels would coat an area of 779 square km (192 thousand acres). It would form a ‘puddle’ 31.5 km across. This is about:&lt;br /&gt;
• Half the area of Greater London&lt;br /&gt;
• 13 x the area of Manhattan, NY&lt;br /&gt;
• A quarter of the area of Rhode Island&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
For more details see: &lt;a href="http://carbonquilt.posterous.com/how-much-oil-is-49-million-barrels-of-oil-get" rel="nofollow"&gt;carbonquilt.posterous.com/how-much-oil-is-49-million-barr...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

