&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/greenpeaceusa09/5080999461/" title="Sub Loaded on Sunrise"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4014/5080999461_400208cc56_m.jpg" width="240" height="166" alt="Sub Loaded on Sunrise" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(L-R) Bosun Philip Lloyd delicately controls the crane as Second mate Sergiy Demydov and Chief Mate Ivo Cuculic  load the 3 ton Dual Deep Worker Submarine aboard The Greenpeace ship Arctic Sunrise at dock in Gulfport, Missssippi, October 13, 2010. Led by Steve Ross of the University of North Carolina Wilmington and Sandra Brooke of the Oregon Institute of Marine Biology, the submarine will be used to study the deep water coral reefs in the vicinity of the BP Deepwater Horizon site and to look how oil has dispersed through the water column and/or onto the sea floor. The status of these corals and surrounding invertebrate communities will be compared to similar areas outside the spill zone.  Teams of independent scientists have been working on the ship conducting a series of scientific research programs that will further understanding of the impacts of both oil and chemical dispersants on the Gulf ecosystem in the aftermath of the BP oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico. A BP leased drilling platform exploded April 20 killing 11 workers and causing a leak of millions of barrels of oil from a wellhead one mile deep 50 miles off the coast of Louisiana. Finally capped in August, the leak was treated with a million gallons of Corexit, a toxic dispersant. Photo by Sean Gardner&lt;br /&gt;
